    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "51130183_942385b9",
        "filename": "snapshot/linux/debug_rendezvous.cc",
        "patchSetId": 11
      },
      "lineNbr": 106,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-07-12T21:25:15Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e We could use the number of mappings as an upper bound on the number of modules.\n\nI think we could easily just keep a std::set of address as we read them.\n\nWe have the same problem in the Windows snapshotter too, where we read linked lists. There\u0027s probably a bug on file for that (can\u0027t check now, I\u0027m on my phone).",
      "parentUuid": "57ea4112_dae4797a",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 106,
        "startChar": 2,
        "endLine": 106,
        "endChar": 28
      },
      "revId": "51972c5ebce5fb5aab3a053df47440ebfeedee2e",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ef7cccdc_9c7d71b5",
        "filename": "snapshot/linux/debug_rendezvous.cc",
        "patchSetId": 11
      },
      "lineNbr": 106,
      "author": {
        "id": 1223274
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-07-12T21:38:43Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yeah, the set is what I first thought of, although I like the idea of the upper bound too (since it may catch other inconsistencies as well)\n\nLikely not in the scope of this change, but if walking linked lists is common enough it\u0027s tempting to consider a \"safe list iterator\" that implements both types of check (upper bound and cycles) - in the same spirit as the \"memory range\" abstraction. What do you think?",
      "parentUuid": "51130183_942385b9",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 106,
        "startChar": 2,
        "endLine": 106,
        "endChar": 28
      },
      "revId": "51972c5ebce5fb5aab3a053df47440ebfeedee2e",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
